{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12643"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.04,0.07,0.06,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107688"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5126"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1870"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-day-old neonate in the Special Care Nursery develops difficulty breathing and feeding. The baby was born prematurely at 36 weeks\u0027 gestation via spontaneous vaginal delivery with a birth weight of 2.2 kg. The mother had a normal antenatal course with no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the neonate appears restless with a respiratory rate of 70/min, heart rate 160/min, blood pressure 55/30 mmHg, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is increased work of breathing with subcostal and intercostal retractions. Auscultation reveals a continuous machinery-like murmur heard best in the left infraclavicular area, which persists during diastole. An echocardiogram shows increased blood flow in the pulmonary artery and a left-to-right shunt at the level of the ductus arteriosus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this neonate\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostaglandin E1","Surgical ligation","Transcatheter closure","Conservative management","Indomethacin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis neonate presents with signs and symptoms consistent with a patent ductus arteriosus (PDA), as demonstrated by the characteristic echocardiographic findings and clinical presentation. \u003Cstrong\u003EIndomethacin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for PDA in preterm neonates. It is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug that inhibits prostaglandin synthesis, promoting closure of the ductus arteriosus. PDA is a condition where the ductus arteriosus, a normal fetal blood vessel connecting the pulmonary artery to the descending aorta, fails to close after birth, leading to increased pulmonary blood flow and potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandin E1\u003C/strong\u003E is used in neonates with duct-dependent congenital heart diseases to maintain ductal patency. It would be contraindicated in this case, as the goal is to close the PDA, not keep it open.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is a definitive treatment option for PDA but is usually reserved for cases where medical treatment has failed or is contraindicated, especially in term babies with PDA. It would be considered overly invasive as a first-line treatment in this preterm neonate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscatheter closure\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive procedure used to treat PDA in selected cases, typically in term babies. It involves placing a device to occlude the ductus arteriosus. This procedure would be too risky and unnecessary as a first-line treatment in a preterm neonate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E involves monitoring the neonate\u0027s clinical status and providing supportive care. While this approach may be appropriate for some cases of PDA, the presence of symptoms and echocardiographic findings in this preterm neonate warrant active treatment with indomethacin as the first step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Indomethacin is the first-line treatment option for patent ductus arteriosus (PDA) in preterm neonates.","Patent ductus arteriosus is characterized by a continuous machinery-like murmur heard best in the left infraclavicular area.","Echocardiogram showing a left-to-right shunt at the level of the ductus arteriosus is diagnostic of PDA."],"references":["Huq A, Rahman A. Cardiac murmurs in children. Aust J Gen Pract [Internet]. 2024 Jul;53(7):453\u201362. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/july/cardiac-murmurs-in-children","Evans P, O\u0027Reilly D, Flyer JN, Soll R, Mitra S. Indomethacin for symptomatic patent ductus arteriosus in preterm infants. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2021 Jan 15;1(1):CD013133. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD013133.pub2. PMID: 33448032; PMCID: PMC8095061."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T07:57:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T07:58:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5126"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107688"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt